<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="18.[157,1529,506,803]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Diagnosis: According to its heavily sclerotized, pitch black palps with entirely fused cymbium and bulbus the genus resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Dumitresco &amp; Georgesco, 1983" authorityName="Dumitresco &amp; Georgesco" authorityYear="1983" box="[834,1526,558,597]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Brignolia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Brignolia Dumitresco &amp; Georgesco, 1983</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Saaristo 2001" authorityName="Saaristo" authorityYear="2001" box="[225,556,609,648]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Lisna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Lisna 
<bibRefCitation author="Saaristo, M. I." box="[329,556,609,648]" journalOrPublisher="Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="307 - 358" part="32" refString="- &quot; - 2001: Dwarf hunting spiders or the Oonopidae (Arachnida, Araneae) of Seychelles. Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution 32: 307 - 358." title="Dwarf hunting spiders or the Oonopidae (Arachnida, Araneae) of Seychelles" type="journal article" year="2001">Saaristo 2001</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
but the structure of bulbal elements of the male palp are more like in 
<taxonomicName box="[355,510,660,699]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Opopaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Opopaea</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[519,601,661,700]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
which, on the other hand, has normally sclerotized male palps with strongly swollen palpal patella, Also the large, oval-shaped, shallow depression on sternum may be of generic value.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
